Step Functions: workflow orchestration.

A workflow that chains a few Lambda functions usually starts as Lambda A calling Lambda B calling Lambda C. It works on day one and turns into a swamp by month three: every function has its own retry logic, error handling is inconsistent, there's no way to see which step failed, and long-running flows hit Lambda's fifteen-minute ceiling. Step Functions is the managed answer. You describe the workflow as a state machine in Amazon States Language, or A-S-L, a J-SON definition of states and transitions. Step Functions runs the state machine, invokes each step, retries on failure with your configured policies, and shows the full execution history in the console.

There are several state types. Task invokes a Lambda or calls an AWS service directly. Choice branches on input data, like an if/else. Wait pauses for a duration or until a timestamp. Parallel runs multiple branches at once and waits for all. And Map iterates over an array, applying a sub-workflow to each element. The error-handling story is the main reason Step Functions exists. Retry attaches rules to a Task, naming error types, an interval, a max attempt count, and a backoff rate; a typical config of two seconds, three attempts, and two-times backoff absorbs most transient failures, like Lambda throttles or DynamoDB throughput errors, with no application code. And Catch routes to a specific handler state when retries are exhausted. Together, they turn a try/catch tangle into a declarative part of the workflow.

There are two workflow types. Standard runs up to one year, is exactly-once per state, is priced per state transition, and keeps its history forever; it's for business workflows like order fulfilment, approvals, and data pipelines. Express runs up to five minutes, is at-least-once or at-most-once, is priced per duration, and handles a hundred thousand-plus starts per second; it's for high-volume short flows like streaming and I-o-T event processing. And the wait-for-task-token pattern pauses a workflow for a human approval or an external callback, for as long as needed.
